The LaTeX Project Public License (LPPL) is the license under which
the LaTeX base system and various other LaTeX packages are
distributed.

You may use this license for any program that you have written and
wish to distribute.  This license may be particularly suitable if
your program is a LaTeX package or a TeX-related program.  However,
it may also be suitable for other kinds of programs.

The LaTeX Project Public License gives you the freedom to distribute
your program under the terms of this license or, at your option,
under the terms of any later version of the LaTeX Project Public
License which is published by the LaTeX3 Project.

In order to use this license for your program you must ensure that
your program (or a modified version of it) is a work "made in the
context of the LaTeX Project".  This means that either:

1. your program calls, or is called by, other LaTeX Project
   programs; or

2. your program interprets (or edits/changes/work with) files that
   are (primarily) used by LaTeX Project programs; or

3. your program is primarily intended for use with LaTeX Project
   programs or with files that are (primarily) used by LaTeX Project
   programs.

A typical example of a program "made in the context of the LaTeX
Project" is a package that is intended to be used with LaTeX (i.e.,
with the program `latex' or with one of the LaTeX packages) or with
a LaTeX document class.

